[49m[38;5;10m+     50[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     51[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## The Technology: IRB-Bounded Conversational Recruitment With Pre-Screening, Equity Discipline, and Coordinator Handoff
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     52[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     53[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Why Clinical Trial Recruitment Has Stayed Coordinator-Centric, And Why That Has Not Worked Well
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     54[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     55[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Clinical trial recruitment, as a workflow, has been a coordinator-and-clinic-centric problem for as long as clinical trials have existed. The reason is structural. Every patient-facing word about a trial is regulated. The IRB reviews and approves the protocol, the consent form, the recruitment flyer, the recruitment letter, the recruitment script, the recruitment email, and (where applicable) the recruitment social-media post. The IRB approval is specific to the language and the format; rewriting the language is not allowed without re-submission. The coordinator who recruits patients in person is reading from an IRB-approved script (or is supposed to be). The patient who reads the recruitment flyer is reading IRB-approved content. The patient who clicks through to ClinicalTrials.gov is reading content that was filed with the FDA and is, in some cases, IRB-reviewed. <!-- TODO: verify; the IRB review process for patient-facing recruitment materials is governed by 45 CFR 46 (the Common Rule) for federally-supported research, 21 CFR 56 for FDA-regulated research, and applicable institutional IRB policies; specific review requirements vary --> The system is designed to protect patients from being misled, oversold, coerced, or recruited into research they do not understand. The system also makes the recruitment funnel slow, expensive, and operationally rigid in ways that have unintended consequences for both trial timelines and patient access.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     56[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     57[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The first generation of digital recruitment tools, roughly 2005 through 2015, was the trial-listing portal. The institution's research office maintained a website listing open trials. Each trial had a description (IRB-approved), inclusion and exclusion criteria (often verbatim from the protocol), and a contact form. Patients who arrived at the site mostly arrived because they searched for their condition, found the institution's research page, and clicked through. The conversion rate from "patient arrives at trial page" to "patient submits contact form" was typically very low. <!-- TODO: verify; conversion rates from passive recruitment-portal listings to coordinator-contacted patients are documented in research-operations literature with specific figures varying widely --> The patients who did contact the institution were often poorly-prepared for the screening conversation, sometimes ineligible for reasons that were stated on the trial page (which they had not read carefully), and sometimes interested in trials they were not actually eligible for at all (which they had searched for and found despite the eligibility mismatch).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     58[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     59[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The second generation, roughly 2015 through 2022, was chart-mining recruitment. The institution's research informatics team built tools that mined the EHR for ICD-10 codes, lab values, medication histories, and other structured indicators that suggested a patient might be eligible for an open trial. The tools produced lists of potentially-eligible patients per trial. The lists went to coordinators, who were supposed to contact the patients. The contact, when it happened, was typically by phone or by patient-portal message. The conversion from "patient on the list" to "patient contacted" was poor (the lists were often longer than coordinators could work through), and the conversion from "patient contacted" to "patient screened" was poor for the recruitment-funnel reasons described in the problem statement. The tools produced more patient names than the recruitment workflow could handle. The bottleneck moved from "find candidate patients" to "contact and pre-screen candidate patients," and the second bottleneck was harder to solve with the tools available at the time.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     60[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     61[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The thing that changed the workflow shape is, again, large language models that can carry on a coherent, sustained, IRB-bounded conversation. A conversational tool, deployed with careful institutional governance, can take a patient who has expressed interest (either through a portal click, a chart-mining-driven outreach, a clinic-based referral, or a community-engagement contact) and walk them through the trial description in plain language, answer the questions they actually have, conduct the IRB-approved pre-screening interview in a conversational form rather than as a paper script, capture their preferred contact information for the next step, and warmly hand off the plausibly-eligible interested candidates to a research coordinator. The LLM is not a coordinator. The LLM is, in the right product design, a tool that lets the coordinator workforce operate at a substantially larger scale by handling the repetitive, scriptable, IRB-bounded portions of the recruitment funnel and surfacing the higher-yield candidates for coordinator engagement.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     62[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     63[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The architectural shift is from "passive listing plus phone tag" to "conversational interface that delivers IRB-approved content and pre-screens with discipline." The bot's value is concentrated in three places: the consistency and IRB-fidelity of the recruitment communication (the bot delivers approved content with version stamping; coordinators sometimes paraphrase and sometimes drift over time), the lower-activation-energy access to the funnel (the patient who would not pick up the phone will sometimes type into a chat), and the operational-reach extension (the patient population that the coordinator workforce alone cannot reach can sometimes be served by a bot-plus-coordinator hybrid that the workforce alone could not).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     64[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     65[0m:[38;5;10m[49m A note on what conversational trial recruitment is and is not, because the category has been confused by a wave of products that look similar from the outside and behave very differently from the inside. The careful end of the spectrum is institutional, IRB-bounded, multi-trial recruitment with rigorous content-versioning, pre-screening discipline, equity monitoring, and coordinator-workflow integration: think tools deployed by academic medical centers, integrated delivery networks, and major sponsor-CRO partnerships under institutional oversight. The middle of the spectrum is single-sponsor or single-CRO recruitment platforms that are operationally disciplined but vary in IRB-content fidelity. The risky end of the spectrum is general-purpose patient-engagement chatbots that have been retrofitted to recruit for trials without the IRB-content discipline, the pre-screening discipline, or the regulatory oversight; these have produced documented incidents involving misrepresentation of trial details, inappropriate pre-screening questions, and recruitment communications that the IRB had not reviewed. <!-- TODO: verify; the regulatory-incident history of patient-recruitment software includes FDA warning letters and IRB-determined non-compliance findings; specific incidents and outcomes vary --> This recipe is firmly in the careful end of the spectrum. The architectural decisions are, in part, decisions about which end of the spectrum the product lives on.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     66[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     67[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### What a Trial Recruitment Bot Actually Does
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     68[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     69[0m:[38;5;10m[49m A trial recruitment bot is a tool-using LLM with a system prompt that tells it which assistant it is, the patient's authenticated context if available (existing diagnoses, current medications, recent labs and imaging, demographics with appropriate consent), the active trial catalog metadata, and access to a structured library of IRB-approved trial-specific content (descriptions, key facts, frequently-asked-questions, pre-screening protocols, consent-document references). The conversation surface is patient-initiated for most volume, with optional bot-initiated outreach where the institution has a chart-mining or referral-based recruitment program and the patient has consented to research-recruitment outreach in advance.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     70[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     71[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The bot's task surface decomposes roughly as follows.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     72[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     73[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Entry and disclosure.** The patient arrives at the bot through one of several pathways: clicking on a trial from the institution's research-recruitment portal, clicking on a trial from a chart-mining-driven outreach message they received with consent, walking up to a tablet in a clinic waiting area, or following a link from a community-engagement event or social-media post that the IRB has approved. The bot's first response includes the disclosures that are non-negotiable for trial recruitment: identifies as a chat tool and not a person, states clearly that it provides IRB-approved information about a research study, names the principal investigator and the institution running the trial, names the sponsor, includes a link to the trial's ClinicalTrials.gov entry, states clearly that participation is voluntary, names the path back out (the patient can stop at any time), and reinforces that the conversation does not constitute consent and does not bind the patient to participation. The patient acknowledges or continues. The disclosure is not boilerplate; it is IRB-approved language reviewed by the institutional regulatory office.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     74[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     75[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Trial selection and overview.** The bot identifies which trial the patient is interested in (typically pre-determined by the entry pathway, but for portal-entry conversations may require a clarifying turn). The bot delivers the IRB-approved trial overview in plain language: what condition the trial is studying, what the investigational intervention is, what the trial design is at a high level (placebo-controlled, dose-comparison, open-label, randomized, blinded, etc.), what participation involves at a high level (visit frequency, total duration, what kinds of activities), what the known and potential risks are, what the known and potential benefits are (with appropriate caveats; trials cannot guarantee benefit), what the compensation structure is (per visit, total, in language the patient can understand), and what the patient's choices are (participate, do not participate, ask more questions, talk to a coordinator now, take time to think about it). The overview is grounded in IRB-approved content; the bot does not freestyle.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     76[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     77[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Patient-initiated questions within scope.** The patient can ask questions about the trial. The bot answers within scope, drawing from the IRB-approved frequently-asked-questions content and the trial's protocol summary (with appropriate access controls; the full protocol is generally not patient-facing, but the patient-facing content drawn from it is). The bot answers factual questions about the trial, the institution, the principal investigator, the sponsor, the timeline, the visit schedule, the compensation, the insurance-coverage interaction, the post-trial access policy (where applicable), the data-sharing posture, and the patient's right to withdraw. The bot does not answer questions that should be addressed by the coordinator or the principal investigator (specific medical questions about the patient's situation; clinical-judgment questions about whether participation is right for the patient; speculative questions about results; questions outside the scope of the IRB-approved patient-facing content).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     78[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     79[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **IRB-approved pre-screening interview.** When the patient is ready, the bot conducts the trial's IRB-approved pre-screening interview. The pre-screening protocol is a defined set of questions that the IRB has reviewed and approved as appropriate for pre-screening (typically eligibility-relevant questions that do not require clinical examination or laboratory data the patient could not be expected to know). For a dermatology trial: questions about the patient's diagnosis, duration of disease, prior therapies tried, current therapies, recent infections, pregnancy status (where relevant), age, and a few other criteria-relevant items. For an oncology trial: questions about the patient's diagnosis, stage, prior treatment, current treatment, performance status, and other items. The pre-screening protocol is per-trial; the bot retrieves the IRB-approved protocol for the active trial and conducts the interview in conversational form. The bot does not skip questions, does not invent questions, and does not change the wording in ways the IRB has not approved. Ambiguous answers trigger a clarifying turn within the IRB-approved follow-up language; persistent ambiguity is handed off to a coordinator.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     80[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     81[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Pre-screening result and next-step framing.** Based on the patient's answers, the bot computes a pre-screening result: plausibly eligible (proceed to coordinator handoff for the formal screening visit), possibly ineligible (the bot does not give a definitive ineligibility determination because final eligibility requires the formal screening visit; the bot may indicate that the patient does not appear to meet certain criteria and offer next steps), or indeterminate (some answers were ambiguous; coordinator review needed). The framing of the result is IRB-approved language; the bot does not diagnose ineligibility, does not editorialize, and does not characterize the patient as a "good candidate" or a "bad fit." The bot delivers the result with appropriate disclaimers (the formal eligibility determination is made by the study team after the screening visit; the pre-screening is preliminary; the patient is welcome to ask more questions; the patient can decide at any point not to proceed).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     82[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     83[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Coordinator handoff for plausibly-eligible interested candidates.** When the pre-screening is positive and the patient is interested in proceeding, the bot collects the patient's preferred contact information (with explicit consent for the coordinator to contact them about this trial), summarizes the conversation in a structured handoff payload, and routes to the coordinator queue. The handoff is warm where the platform supports it: the bot can offer the patient a same-conversation handoff to a coordinator, can offer a scheduled callback, or can offer a portal-message follow-up. The handoff payload includes the conversation transcript, the pre-screening answer set, the active trial-content version, and the patient's preferences. The coordinator receives the patient already pre-screened and prepared for the screening visit conversation.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     84[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     85[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Off-ramps for ineligible, uninterested, or undecided patients.** Patients who pre-screen as possibly ineligible are offered alternatives where appropriate (related trials they may be eligible for; a request to be notified of future trials they may be eligible for if they consent to that; general information about the institution's research program). Patients who decide they are not interested are thanked respectfully and offered alternative resources. Patients who want to think about it are offered the opportunity to come back later, to receive the IRB-approved consent document for review, or to schedule a no-pressure call with a coordinator for further questions. The respectful off-ramp is part of trust-building with the patient population over time; patients who feel respectfully handled when they decline this trial sometimes return for future trials.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     86[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     87[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Equity and representativeness as architectural design.** The bot's recruitment funnel is monitored for representativeness against the trial's enrollment-diversity targets and against the underlying patient-population demographics. Per-cohort engagement rates, pre-screening positivity rates, coordinator-handoff conversion rates, and study-completion rates are tracked by demographic axes (race, ethnicity, sex, age, language, geography, socioeconomic indicators, insurance type). When the bot's funnel is failing to reach population segments, the institutional response is not "the bot is doing its job"; the institutional response is to investigate the cause (content-language gap, channel gap, trust gap, accessibility gap, structural barrier) and adjust. The equity monitoring is a launch-gate metric, not a post-launch dashboard.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     88[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     89[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Audit and post-market surveillance.** Every conversation produces an audit record (transcript, IRB-approved-content version, pre-screening-protocol version, pre-screening result, handoff status, patient consent for further contact). The audit feeds compliance review, IRB reporting (where the IRB requires post-market reporting on the recruitment tool), institutional regulatory review, and the equity-monitoring pipeline. Where the institution has the data integration, the bot's pre-screening result is correlated with the patient's actual screening-visit outcome (did the patient come in, was the patient enrolled, did the patient complete the trial) for ongoing pre-screening-protocol calibration.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     90[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     91[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Why a Generic LLM Cannot Run a Trial Recruitment Bot
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     92[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     93[0m:[38;5;10m[49m A naive product approach would be: take a generalist LLM, give it a chat surface, paste in some trial information, and have it talk to potential participants. This breaks in several specific ways, each of which has clinical, ethical, and regulatory consequences.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     94[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     95[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no IRB-approved-content discipline.** The IRB approves specific language, in specific formats, for specific patient-facing communications. A generalist LLM paraphrases, summarizes, and generates novel language as part of its normal operation. None of that language has been IRB-approved. The bot must deliver IRB-approved content with version stamping; freestyling trial-related content is non-compliant. The architectural pattern is to treat the IRB-approved content as a structured corpus, retrieve verbatim or near-verbatim passages, and constrain the LLM to deliver them as written rather than rewriting them.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     96[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     97[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no theory of consent versus pre-screening.** Informed consent for trial participation is a specific regulated process distinct from pre-screening. A generalist LLM, asked to conduct a "trial enrollment conversation," will drift into consent-flavored territory: walking the patient through the consent document, asking for the patient's agreement to participate, treating the conversation as if it were the consent process. The bot must explicitly stay in pre-screening territory, must explicitly defer the consent process to the coordinator, and must not collect anything that would constitute consent. The scope discipline is enforced through prompts, output safety, and reviewer audits.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     98[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     99[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model misrepresents trials when grounding is weak.** A bot freestyling trial details is delivering content the IRB has not reviewed. The misrepresentation may understate risks, overstate benefits, mischaracterize the trial design, misstate eligibility criteria, or invent compensation amounts. Each is a regulatory and ethical violation. The IRB-approved-content RAG with strict citation grounding is the architectural floor; the LLM delivers content from the approved library, not from its parametric memory.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    100[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    101[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no theory of the inducement-versus-coercion line.** Recruitment communications must not coerce, unduly influence, or mislead patients about benefits. A generalist LLM, prompted to be helpful in encouraging participation, can drift into language that emphasizes benefits over risks, that uses urgency framing inappropriately, or that suggests the patient should participate because of the bot's recommendation. The bot's language is calibrated for informed-decision-making support, not for enrollment-quota optimization. The institutional review of bot output specifically tags inducement-flavor language as a failure mode.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    102[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    103[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no theory of vulnerable populations.** Some patient populations have specific protections under the Common Rule and other regulations: children (with parental permission and child assent considerations), pregnant women, prisoners, patients with diminished capacity for consent, and others. <!-- TODO: verify; vulnerable-population protections in U.S. clinical research are governed by 45 CFR 46 Subparts B, C, and D, and applicable institutional policies; specific protections vary --> The bot's design accounts for the trial's specific population. Adult-only-trial bots include eligibility-screening-out for minors with appropriate routing. Pediatric-trial bots include parental-consent and child-assent flows. The vulnerable-population posture is reviewed by the IRB and the institutional regulatory office.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    104[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    105[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has clinical-decision-rule arithmetic problems for eligibility computation.** Eligibility criteria sometimes involve computed values: BMI, eGFR, performance status conversions, duration calculations, lab-value thresholds. The LLM does this poorly. Deterministic eligibility-computation tools encapsulate the arithmetic; the LLM gathers inputs and presents the computed result.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    106[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    107[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has compliance implications specific to research recruitment.** The conversation contains PHI and sometimes contains research-specific disclosures (the patient's interest in research participation, their willingness to consider experimental treatment, their prior research history). Some research records have specific privacy considerations beyond standard HIPAA; trials run under a Certificate of Confidentiality have additional protections that affect how the conversation can be subpoenaed or shared. <!-- TODO: verify; Certificates of Confidentiality issued by NIH and other agencies provide specific privacy protections for research records; specific protections vary --> The audit, retention, access-control, and downstream-research-workflow story has to handle each of these.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    108[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    109[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no theory of consenting-the-consent versus consenting-recruitment-engagement.** Engaging with the bot is itself an interaction the patient is entering into; the institution typically requires the patient to consent to the recruitment-engagement-with-the-bot separately from the eventual consent to participate in the trial. The recruitment-engagement consent covers: the bot's nature as a chat tool, the data the bot collects, the data-sharing posture (the institution shares pre-screening data with the coordinator team and, in some configurations, with the trial sponsor; the patient consents to this sharing), the data retention, the patient's right to withdraw their information, and the patient's understanding that engagement does not bind them to trial participation. The recruitment-engagement consent is itself IRB-approved.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    110[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    111[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no theory of equity-as-design.** A bot deployed without explicit equity monitoring may exacerbate the historical underrepresentation of clinical trial populations. The bot's per-cohort engagement and conversion monitoring is not a nice-to-have; it is a launch-gate primitive. Where the bot is failing to reach specific population segments, the institutional response is structural (adjust the language, the channels, the partnerships, the content) rather than declarative ("we tried").
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    112[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    113[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no theory of when the recruitment conversation should pause.** Some patients want to think about it. Some patients want to talk to family. Some patients want to read the consent document offline. Some patients are not ready to make a decision in the same conversation. The bot's design supports respectful pausing, picking up later, and asynchronous engagement. The bot does not pressure for same-session decisions.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    114[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    115[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no theory of when the conversation should end.** A patient who has decided not to participate should be respectfully thanked, offered relevant alternatives if appropriate, and not pressured to reconsider. A patient who has been pre-screened as possibly ineligible should be respectfully informed and offered next steps. A patient who has crossed into out-of-scope territory (asking for medical advice, asking the bot to consent them, asking about a different patient's case) should be redirected. The conversation-ending heuristics are reviewed by clinical-research leadership and tuned with operations.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    116[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    117[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no theory of cross-trial routing.** A patient asking about Trial A may be eligible for Trial B. A patient pre-screening out of Trial A for a specific reason may be a fit for Trial C. The cross-trial-routing logic is governed by institutional policy (which trials are appropriate to mention, which require explicit re-consent for cross-trial information sharing, which are blinded to the patient's prior trial-engagement history). Generalist LLMs may volunteer cross-trial information inappropriately; the bot's logic is constrained by institutional policy.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    118[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    119[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The model has no theory of mandatory-reporting and crisis-screening adjacencies.** Trial recruitment conversations sometimes surface mental-health crisis (a patient with major depressive disorder seeking enrollment in a depression trial may be in active crisis), suicidal ideation, intimate-partner violence, or other disclosures with mandatory-reporting implications. The bot's continuous crisis screening (carried forward from recipe 11.8) routes these appropriately, with the trial-recruitment context preserved and the licensed-clinician handoff prioritized.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    120[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    121[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### What the Recruitment Bot Has To Do That the Previous Bots Did Not
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    122[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    123[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Recipes 11.1 through 11.9 established the patterns this recipe inherits: input safety screening with continuous emergency screening, identity verification, tool-use orchestration, output safety screening, audit logging, per-cohort monitoring, scope discipline, prompt-injection defense, graceful degradation, longitudinal-context loading where applicable, citation grounding, warm handoff infrastructure. The recruitment bot adds eight structural commitments those recipes did not have.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    124[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    125[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **IRB-approved-content corpus governance with version control and re-approval cycle.** Every patient-facing word the bot says about a trial is IRB-approved content with version control. When the IRB approves an amendment, the corpus is updated with the new version and the old version is archived; the conversation log records which content version was active for any given conversation. The corpus governance is owned jointly by the principal investigators, the research-operations team, the IRB office, and the institutional regulatory team.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    126[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    127[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Pre-screening-as-script-not-improvisation discipline.** The pre-screening protocol is per-trial, IRB-approved, and conducted as a defined question sequence with IRB-approved follow-up clarifications. The bot does not improvise pre-screening questions, does not skip questions, and does not change the wording in ways the IRB has not approved.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    128[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    129[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Consent-versus-pre-screening boundary enforcement.** The bot conducts pre-screening; the bot does not consent. The boundary is enforced through prompts, output safety, and reviewer audits. Crossing the boundary is a regulatory violation; the institutional review specifically tags consent-territory drift as a failure mode.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    130[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    131[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Equity-as-design as architectural primitive.** Per-cohort engagement, pre-screening positivity, coordinator-handoff conversion, and study-completion rates are monitored with explicit demographic axes. Disparities trigger investigation and remediation rather than acceptance. The equity discipline is reviewed by clinical-research leadership, the IRB (where applicable), and the institutional equity office.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    132[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    133[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Coordinator-workflow integration with structured handoff.** The bot's output feeds the coordinator's workflow. The handoff payload, the queue management, the call-back scheduling, the case management, and the trial-management-system integration are all part of the bot's deployment scope. The coordinator does not start over; the patient does not start over.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    134[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    135[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Cross-trial-routing logic governed by institutional policy.** The bot's behavior when a patient may be eligible for multiple trials, when a patient pre-screens out of one trial but may fit another, and when a patient asks about cross-trial alternatives is governed by institutional policy reviewed by the IRB and the regulatory office.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    136[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    137[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Vulnerable-population-aware design.** Adult-only-trial bots screen out minors. Pediatric-trial bots include parental-consent and child-assent flows. Trials enrolling pregnant women, prisoners, or patients with diminished capacity for consent have specific design considerations. The bot's per-trial configuration includes the trial's population specification.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    138[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    139[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Outcome-correlation pipeline with multi-trial scope and IRB review.** The bot's pre-screening accuracy, the coordinator-handoff conversion, the screening-visit completion rate, the trial-enrollment rate, the study-completion rate, and the demographic representativeness of the recruited population are correlated and reported. Where the IRB requires it, the institution reports recruitment-tool outcomes back to the IRB.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    140[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    141[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The rest is largely the same as the previous chapter 11 recipes.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    142[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    143[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### The Recruitment Reality
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    144[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    145[0m:[38;5;10m[49m A few notes on what makes trial recruitment specifically harder than the other patient-facing bot use cases.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    146[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    147[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The IRB review process is the rate-limiting step.** Every word the bot says about a trial is IRB-reviewed. New trials require new IRB submissions. Protocol amendments require IRB amendments. New languages require IRB translation review. New channels require IRB review. The IRB's turnaround time on the bot's recruitment content is typically multi-week per submission. Mitigation: design the IRB submission for the bot itself as a long-lived "umbrella" submission covering the bot's general behavior, with per-trial submissions covering the trial-specific content; build content-versioning infrastructure that supports the IRB's versioning expectations; build a dedicated content-development and IRB-submission pipeline owned by research operations.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    148[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    149[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The institutional governance is multi-team.** Principal investigators, research-operations, the IRB office, the institutional regulatory office, the legal office, the privacy office, the equity office (where one exists), the IT security office, the clinical leadership for the therapeutic areas the bot serves, the institution's malpractice insurer (where research-recruitment is covered), and the trial sponsor (in industry-sponsored trials) all have a stake. Mitigation: explicit operational ownership across teams; clear decision rights; named approvers; regular cross-team review.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    150[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    151[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Sponsor relationships add complexity.** Industry-sponsored trials have sponsor-specified recruitment requirements, sponsor review of recruitment materials, sponsor-required reporting on recruitment outcomes, and sometimes sponsor-provided recruitment-content templates that need IRB adaptation. The bot's design accommodates sponsor-specific configurations per trial. Mitigation: per-trial configuration discipline; sponsor-content review process; explicit handling of sponsor-specific data-sharing requirements with patient consent.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    152[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    153[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The patient population is broader than active patients.** Recruitment reaches active patients (the institution's own patients, often with chart-mining-driven outreach), past patients (including those who have moved or aged out of active care), and non-patients (community members responding to outreach, social-media posts, search-engine ads where the IRB has approved them). Mitigation: per-population content adaptation; channel-mix design; non-patient authentication and PHI-handling considerations.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    154[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    155[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The compensation-structure conversation is sensitive.** Patients respond to compensation; the IRB is sensitive to compensation that could constitute undue inducement. The bot describes compensation factually in IRB-approved language, does not lead with compensation, and does not use compensation as the primary motivator. <!-- TODO: verify; IRB and FDA guidance on payment to research subjects is documented in FDA's guidance for IRBs and clinical investigators; specific limits and structures vary --> Mitigation: compensation language is IRB-approved verbatim text; review specifically tags compensation-leading language as a failure mode.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    156[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    157[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Equity goals must translate into operational design.** Sponsors and regulators increasingly require diversity action plans for trials. <!-- TODO: verify; FDA Diversity Action Plan guidance for clinical trials has continued to evolve; specific requirements vary by trial --> The bot's equity monitoring is a means to the operational end of recruiting representative populations, not a metric to optimize for its own sake. Mitigation: equity monitoring tied to specific trial-population targets; investigation-and-remediation discipline when targets are missed; partnership with community organizations and trusted-messengers where appropriate.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    158[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    159[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Cultural competence and linguistic accessibility are non-optional.** Trial populations are often disproportionately non-English-speaking, non-U.S.-born, or culturally distinct from the recruitment-team's demographic. Mitigation: per-language content with clinically-validated translations; per-cultural-context content adaptation reviewed by community advisors; per-cohort engagement monitoring as a leading indicator of cultural-fit gaps.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    160[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    161[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Trust gaps are a substantial barrier.** Communities with documented historical mistreatment by the research enterprise (Black Americans in the wake of Tuskegee, indigenous communities, immigrant communities in some contexts, LGBTQ+ communities for some research areas) have legitimate, well-founded skepticism of clinical trial recruitment. <!-- TODO: verify; the historical foundations of mistrust of medical research in specific U.S. communities are extensively documented in academic literature; specific events and ongoing impact vary --> Mitigation: institutional commitment to community engagement; transparency about the trial, the institution, the sponsor, and the patient's rights; partnership with trusted community organizations; recognition that a bot alone cannot rebuild trust that has been broken over generations.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    162[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    163[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Long-term outcome demonstration is multi-year work.** A trial that takes 18 months to complete enrollment cannot be evaluated for bot-driven recruitment-acceleration in less than 18 months. A study-completion-rate effect is observed at trial completion plus follow-up. Mitigation: realistic time-horizon expectations; phased-deployment strategy with early indicators (engagement rates, pre-screening conversion, coordinator-handoff rates) preceding the long-term outcomes.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    164[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    165[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Liability exposure is meaningfully higher than in non-recruitment bots.** A bot that misrepresents a trial, that improperly induces enrollment, that fails to surface a relevant exclusion criterion, that recruits a patient who should have been screened out for safety reasons, or that violates IRB-approved content discipline is a liability exposure. Mitigation: rigorous content discipline; per-trial review process; named ownership; institutional regulatory and legal review; institutional malpractice insurer involvement where relevant.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    166[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    167[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Where the Field Has Moved
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    168[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    169[0m:[38;5;10m[49m A few practical updates worth knowing.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    170[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    171[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **FDA Diversity Action Plans are a regulatory expectation.** The FDA has finalized guidance requiring sponsors of certain clinical trials to submit diversity action plans describing their goals for enrollment of historically-underrepresented populations and their strategies for achieving those goals. <!-- TODO: verify; FDA Diversity Action Plan guidance has continued to evolve and the specific requirements depend on trial type and applicability date; the FDA's resources on Drug Trials Snapshots and clinical trial diversity provide current information --> Recruitment-bot deployments increasingly need to demonstrably support these plans through equity-monitoring infrastructure and demographically-aware recruitment strategy.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    172[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    173[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Decentralized and hybrid clinical trial models are growing.** Trials that conduct some or all visits remotely (telehealth visits, in-home visits, retail-pharmacy visits, retail-laboratory visits) have grown substantially since 2020. <!-- TODO: verify; the FDA's guidance on decentralized clinical trials and the broader industry adoption of hybrid models has continued to evolve --> Recruitment bots support these models by adapting the visit-burden description, the geographic-eligibility scope, and the coordinator-handoff routing to the trial's operational model.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    174[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    175[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **ClinicalTrials.gov registration is required for most U.S. trials.** Trials of FDA-regulated products must register on ClinicalTrials.gov and report results within specified timelines. <!-- TODO: verify; ClinicalTrials.gov registration and results-reporting requirements are governed by FDAAA Section 801 and 42 CFR Part 11; specific trial applicability varies --> The bot links to the ClinicalTrials.gov entry for each trial and leverages the registry's structured data where appropriate.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    176[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    177[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Patient-recruitment-software products have proliferated.** The category includes general-purpose engagement platforms retrofitted for trials, sponsor-specific recruitment portals, CRO-provided recruitment-platform services, and academic-medical-center-built tools. <!-- TODO: verify; the patient-recruitment-software landscape includes products from Antidote, TrialSpark, Acurian, Medable, ObvioHealth, and many others, with widely-varying capability sets and regulatory postures --> Institutions deploying recruitment bots typically run a hybrid: build a thin orchestration layer in-house, partner with vendors for trial-content management or community-outreach infrastructure, and integrate with the institutional clinical-trial-management system, EHR, and patient-portal infrastructure.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    178[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    179[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Tool-using LLMs handle IRB-bounded recruitment well when grounded carefully.** The function-calling pattern from the previous chapter 11 recipes maps to recruitment. The LLM produces tool calls that retrieve trial content, retrieve pre-screening protocols, compute eligibility-criterion arithmetic, route to coordinator queues, schedule coordinator callbacks, capture patient consent for data sharing, and post events for downstream operations.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    180[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    181[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Hybrid AI-plus-coordinator deployment is the dominant pattern.** Most operationally-disciplined deployments run a hybrid: AI for initial engagement, education, and pre-screening; coordinator for the formal screening visit, the consent process, and the trial-management work. The economics work because the AI handles the high-volume early-funnel work while the coordinator workforce focuses where their expertise is most needed.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    182[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    183[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Equity monitoring is increasingly a published expectation.** Sponsors, IRBs, and academic institutions are increasingly publishing recruitment-tool equity-monitoring methodologies, target metrics, and outcome data. <!-- TODO: verify; the publication landscape on recruitment-tool equity continues to evolve; academic literature, FDA guidance, and sponsor-published diversity action plans contain current information --> Per-cohort monitoring with explicit equity focus is essential.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    184[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    185[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Outcome reporting back to the IRB is increasingly expected.** Where the IRB requires it, the recruitment-tool's outcomes (engagement, pre-screening, conversion, demographic representativeness, study-completion correlation) are reported back to the IRB on a defined cadence. Mitigation: build the outcome-reporting pipeline as part of deployment scope, not as a phase-2 enhancement.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    186[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    187[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Build-vs-buy is mature for some segments.** Several mature commercial vendors offer recruitment-platform products at major-academic-medical-center and major-CRO scale, with EHR integration, ClinicalTrials.gov integration, IRB-content-management workflows, and equity-monitoring infrastructure. Most major institutions deploying in this space run a hybrid: build a thin-orchestration layer in-house, partner with vendors for licensed content-management or community-outreach infrastructure, and integrate with the institution's clinical-trial-management system, EHR, and patient-portal infrastructure.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    188[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    189[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
